            <!-- EXPLANATION CONTENT -->
            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this taxes calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This page is designed as a <strong>taxes hub</strong>: instead
                of focusing on a single jurisdiction, it gives you quick,
                generic estimates for the most common tax types and then points
                you to more detailed tools when you need them.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Income tax (progressive brackets)</h3>
              <p>
                Many countries use a
                <strong>progressive income tax</strong> system: income is split
                into bands (brackets), and each band is taxed at a different
                rate. Only the income that falls inside a band is taxed at that
                band’s rate.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Illustrative bracket model used here:
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc ml-5 mb-0">
                  <li>0% on the first $10,000</li>
                  <li>10% on $10,001 – $40,000</li>
                  <li>20% on $40,001 – $100,000</li>
                  <li>30% on income above $100,000</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator applies these bands to your
                <strong>taxable income</strong> and returns:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Total tax</strong> – sum of tax from each band.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective tax rate</strong> – total tax ÷ income.
                </li>
                <li><strong>After‑tax income</strong> – income minus tax.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Sales tax</h3>
              <p>
                Sales tax is usually a <strong>flat percentage</strong> applied
                to the purchase price of taxable goods and services. Some items
                may be exempt or taxed at reduced rates depending on your
                jurisdiction.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Sales tax formula</p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Tax} = \text{Price before tax} \times
                  \dfrac{\text{Rate}}{100}\)
                  <br />
                  \(\text{Total price} = \text{Price before tax} + \text{Tax}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Payroll / paycheck withholding</h3>
              <p>
                Employers typically withhold several types of tax and
                contributions from each paycheck:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Income tax (national / federal, and sometimes state or local).
                </li>
                <li>Social security or pension contributions.</li>
                <li>
                  Other deductions such as retirement plans or health insurance.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This tool lets you approximate the impact of these deductions as
                simple percentages of gross pay, so you can see your
                <strong>net pay per period</strong> and
                <strong>annual net pay</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Self‑employment tax</h3>
              <p>
                Self‑employed individuals often pay both the “employee” and
                “employer” portions of social contributions. In the U.S., for
                example, this is commonly referred to as
                <strong>self‑employment tax</strong>.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Self‑employment tax (simplified)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{SE tax} = \text{Net self‑employment income} \times
                  \dfrac{\text{SE rate}}{100}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Real rules may include thresholds, caps, and partial deductions
                of the self‑employment tax from income tax. Always check
                official guidance or consult a professional.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Property tax</h3>
              <p>
                Property tax is usually based on the
                <strong>assessed value</strong> of real estate multiplied by a
                local tax rate.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Property tax formula</p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Annual property tax} = \text{Assessed value} \times
                  \dfrac{\text{Rate}}{100}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Some regions offer exemptions or relief for primary residences,
                seniors, or low‑income households.
              </p>

              <h2>When to use a specialized tax calculator</h2>
              <p>
                Because tax rules are highly jurisdiction‑specific and change
                frequently, you should use dedicated tools when you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Need an accurate estimate for a specific country, state, or
                  province.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Have complex income (business, rental, investments, stock
                  options).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Plan large transactions (home sale, major capital gains,
                  inheritance).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>On CalcDomain you can explore:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <a
